s concealed shapes of truth and possibility. Crucially, Hollander explores how shadows in poetic history become things with a strange substance and life of their own: they acquire the power to console, haunt, stalk, wander, threaten, command, and destroy. Shadow speaks, even sings, revealing to us the lost as much as the hidden self. An extraordinary blend of literary analysis and speculative thought, Hollander’s account of the substance of shadow lays bare the substance of poetry itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aShades and shadows in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ashadows, metaphor, imagery, symbolism, literature, art, popular culture, bible, religion, dante, good and evil, shakespeare, milton, poe, dickinson, eliot, wallace stevens, dreaming, desire, doubt, death, unknown, fear, guilt, shame, secrets, poetry, british, american, renaissance, modern, shades, light, nonfiction, criticism, interpretation.1 aGross, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022635427940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226354309423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226354309/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles